INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '76b8a3cb-fb48-4ff1-90b9-8c45f4d7bc25',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$NATS Message Delivery Guarantees — At-Most-Once, At-Least-Once, and Exactly-Once with JetStream$escape$,
  $escape$Core NATS is fire-and-forget: if a subscriber is offline or slow, messages are dropped — that's at-most-once. No persistence, no retries.

JetStream changes the equation. Configure a durable consumer with `AckPolicy: nats.AckExplicitPolicy` and unacknowledged messages are redelivered after `AckWait` expires — giving you at-least-once. Your handler must be idempotent; duplicate delivery is expected on crash or timeout. Cap retries with `MaxDeliver`.

Exactly-once requires two coordinated halves. On the publisher side, set the `Nats-Msg-Id` header — JetStream deduplicates within the stream's `Duplicates` window (default 2 minutes). On the consumer side, swap `msg.Ack()` for `msg.AckSync()`, which blocks until the server confirms receipt of the ack. Skipping either half gives you at-least-once, not exactly-once.

One critical caveat: the dedup window is finite. A publisher outage longer than the `Duplicates` duration reopens the duplicate risk, so tune it to your worst-case downtime.$escape$,
  $escape$// Publisher: stamp each message with a unique ID for deduplication
msg := nats.NewMsg("orders.created")
msg.Header.Set(nats.MsgIdHdr, uuid.New().String())
msg.Data = payload
js.PublishMsg(msg)

// Consumer: AckExplicit + AckSync = exactly-once
js.Subscribe("orders.created", func(msg *nats.Msg) {
    if err := process(msg.Data); err != nil {
        msg.Nak() // triggers redelivery after AckWait
        return
    }
    msg.AckSync() // blocks until server confirms the ack
}, nats.Durable("orders-processor"), nats.AckExplicit())$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
